comments.text:
I believe it was foul play. 

1. Kris and Lisanne's bones were found close together by the river bank. This would not be possible if Kris died first and Lisanne continued on alone and died separately at another place, another time, or that one of the girls was injured and the other one left to go for help. The rest of the bones were missing, including large bones that could not have been taken by scavengers, there were no large predators in the area, the found bones had no animal teeth marks or marks from being bashed against rocks in the river and Kris' bones were bleached. In 9 weeks the bones shouldn't have been broken up, bleached, and the flesh fully decomposed. 

2. The backpack shows up mysteriously, dry in pristine condition despite being in the jungle for several months, neatly packed with both their phones and bras including a water bottle strangely still half full, the electronics were in working order, and the local woman who found it said it wasn't there the day before. The items in the pack also had 30 other sets of prints on it. It was probably not in the river and washed up or exposed to the elements for 10 weeks.

3. There was a picture missing on their camera that was said to have been deleted on a computer and beyond recovery, it was the only picture between the daytime and nighttime photos. They didn't have a computer and if deleted from the camera, it would still be on the memory card. Unlikely they deleted it because it was an ugly picture and there were other poor quality photos that weren't deleted. Could this picture have shown the killer, something they were not meant to see, a crime, or even both girls together as proof there was a third party? 

4. The call attempts and signal checks were only made during the day and strangely around the same time, no calls were made at night. You would think the calls would've been frantic at sundown and they were the most scared and desperate at night. They also stopped calling their families once they disappeared. The phone logs are inconsistent with the idea they died together or were swept away by the river. Also, there was a gap with no activity on the iPhone between the 7th and 10th, and multiple wrong passcode attempts . 

5. Other bones were found during the search, up to three other people mixed with theirs, and there are two dozen other unsolved disappearances or murders in the area. A local rancher propositioned the girls and was also the one who found their remains a few hours away from his ranch. Kris' shorts were found either folded on a rock or in the river with no sign of decomposition. 

6. 90 strange photos were taken from the camera on the 8th between 1-4 in the morning and only on that night, strangely at an average of 2 minute intervals, with no proof that Lisanne or Kris was the one taking the pictures, with nothing seen in most of the pictures (so we're told). There was a picture of a either dead or incapacitated Kris. They were probably not using the flash to see since the pictures were only taken on one night in the span of a few hours and most were black, no concise message was conveyed either. In the daytime photos, there was a change in mood as Kris looked unhappy and they were going deeper into the jungle, Lisanne is not seen and may or may not have been the one taking the picture. 

7. Panama authorities may have covered up a murder due to corruption, the case was so bizarre and chilling that it would cause public alarm, or not wanting to harm tourism.

Bone bleaching isn't that unusual if the bones were left in an area that received sunlight. Sunlight can bleach bones fairly quickly, especially over weeks. If predators fed on them after death the flesh would loosen and larger predators wouldn't have to use much force that would damage the bone. Smaller predators would be even less likely to damage bone. Worms and insects would finish cleaning the bones, and that can be done in just a few days. The fact that not all the bones were found is evidence of scavengers.

If they were indeed set upon by a third party there's no way they'd be able to attempt 77 emergency calls or even keep their phone. It seems some people want to invoke the most salacious possibility instead of the most likely mundane reason.

This was posted by someone in Reddit in regards to this case. I think it gives you an idea:

Just want to share another hikers recent experience of the same trail to address this myth around it being 'impossible to get lost on':

Oh, it's VERY possible to get lost on the El Pianista, and I'm speaking from experience! I hiked this same trail and got lost just 3 weeks ago while on vacation in Costa Rica and Panama, after hearing about this case. Signs at the base next to the restaurant even say it's prohibited to hike unless for science purposes. You have to cross two streams, and halfway up the trail becomes practically nonexistent. Once I got to the top, about a 3 hour hike without seeing one person, I lost track of the trail and lost my mind within seconds, and began running downhill completely lost. All the vegetation made it impossible to walk at times, I had to climb, crawl and scoot downhill for Two hours before I eventually wandered into someone's property and yelled for help. Honestly, if it wasn't for the fact that I had GPS which I used to guide me towards the direction of town, I'm not sure I would've escaped before nightfall. If they didn't have GPS, they probably lost track of direction completely and accidently wandered off over the other side of the hill, which is nothing but isolated jungle. This case intrigued me and I decided I knew better than these girls and took a shot at adventure, but it was the most terrifying experience of my life. At one point I even leaned my hand against a tree, actually grabbing onto a Green Vine Snake (later found out it's harmless) but that's when I lost my mind completely, screaming, and survival skills kicked in. comments.text:
I am so glad you covered that case I became passionate about a few years ago. I read multiples articles and watched dozen of videos about it. At the very beginning, I was sure there were some kind of foul play involved. But after so many researches, I am pretty positive they died from natural conditions and ended up being eaten (dead or almost dead) by animals. One thing everybody must know about that case is that there is PLENTY of contradictories informations on the internet about it, so don't jump on every details you heard.

Here's my (LONG) theory :

- The girls didn't plan to go for the real big hike that day. They plan it for the day after, with the guide guy (you know, they booked a tour for the day after with a guide and never showed up). The stuff they brought with them shows that they didn't want to go that far (not real food apparently and not a lot of water). The fact that they took the dog with them is a proof as well. Its seems that they just wanted to check the environnement of their future hike with the dog, having a long walk with the animal in this place that, apparently, excited them. Plus I'm not sure that the owner of the dog would have let them go for a real long hiking day with the animal.

- They did go too far anyway and get lost. How ? The dog once again maybe the explanation. It may has run away for some reasons and the girls tried to follow it. It was not their dog so it was not that disciplined with them (and there is a million reasons he would have run away). The girls didn't realise that, at that point, it was so dangerous to leave the trail or whatever is the main path they were following. As they stopped looking for the dog, they check around them and realized they were lost (never being there but everyone seems to say that it is so easy to get lost in the place, so wild, raining, surrounded by enormous trees that hide the light, everything looking the same). I believed this happened a few hours after they left, and that's the moment they did their first 911 call. That fact that they didn't bring that much food and water + the wild environnement may have not helped as well : they were dehydrated, panicking, and every of those conditions did affect their logic, their sense of direction and their capacity of thinking correctly.

- They decided to go the wrong way and that was it : they were definitively lost. The sad thing is they certainly weren't that far at this point. But they decided to follow the wrong direction. 

- They survived that long (6-8 days for Kris, more than 10 days for Lisanne) cause they managed to find water somewhere (rain, trees, rivers). The fact that this water wasn't healthy, once again, took part of making them weak and may explain some bad decisions, accidents (Kris may has fell), things that didn't make really sense ("why they didn't/did do that" etc). About the photos : it can be to check where they were going, to do some lighting to indicated their presence, to scared animals, by Lisanne to remember the place where Kris died... They tried to call, to reach a signal, to make some lights, to do a SOS sign... They were (logically) panicking and moved a lot (to much : it did tired them even more and tend to make them unreachable). On April 3 they could reach a signal and having a 1 or 2 sec call with 911. At that point, they should have stay there as the signal may have came back. But once again, we are not in their heads, they were confused, tired and panicking. 

- Kris passed away first. It can be plenty of reasons : accident, dehydratation, animals, intoxication... Some clues tend to indicate that she felt from a bridge they were attempting to cross (the blood on her head, the photos and the piece of her clothes we may have found near a bridge.. / always saying "may" 'cause as I said, the informations about their remain and their belongings that were found are not so trustworthy). Did she died from that accident ? We don't know. Analyses of the phones shows that April 6-7 is definitely a turning point : it is certainly the day Kris has passed away. We can see that Lisanne tried to used Kris' phone but didn't have the pin code; plus the 77 attempts to use the phone shows that she was definitely panicking at this point. Something tell me that if Kris was slowly dying, she would have gave Lisanne her pin code. If she didn't, it's probably because she died suddenly. Some people are wondering why she would try to get into the phone when she can still call emergencies numbers with an unlock phone... I think we shouldn't even wonder why. I mean, come on ! The poor girl is an a terrible situation, her friend has died, she must be very weak, not really aware of what she is doing... She may wanted to unlock the phone for plenty of reasons as : check the photos, looking for a signal, having access to some infos... Anyway, Lisanne took Kris stuff with her and keep walking (that's why we found Kris' stuff in Lisanne's bag).

- The battery of the phone died on April 11. Lisanne may have survived some days after that, but not a lot. She was alone, with no lights, weak and confused, certainly injured... if she didn't died "naturally", animals probably killed her. I read and article in which an expert said that, judging by her foot we found in its boot and the place where we found some of her remain, she may have died falling from a cliff she tried to climb, probably to be able to look from the top of it to find her way. I personally think she did amazing surviving that long, alone, and it probably would never have happened if she was not the athletic girl she was.

- I personally think animals eat (or kill) both of them. That would explain why most of their parts are missing, and why their remain are kilometers away from each others. It explains as well the fact that the bones are not in the same conditions : they were not eaten by the same animal. Everybody is freaking out on the bleached bone but two things can explain that : it may have been eaten by a snake (this theory is confirmed by experts, bones rejected by snakes may be bleached and that would explain why most of the body is missing) or it may be due to a long stay under the sun.

- About the intact bag : Lisanne died falling from the cliff. Days after, a foot she broke falling get detached from her body (nothing weird about that... just check google), an animal came, ate her, and let the bag and the boot where it was. I know the indigene girl said that it wasn't there the day before... but we shouldn't based an entire theory with the saying of one people. She may have done a mistake, or an other indigene found it before, moved it, then realised that he may be involved by mistake in a crime and left, leaving the bag at an other place. 

- About the other bone(s) and finger print(s) : sources do not agree on this. They MAY have found some "strange DNA or fingers prints" on some of the clothes-flesh-bones of the girls... Nothing sure. Be careful with that bit of information... Animals DNA, man finger print ? The bone they found could be from someone else as this terrible story is nothing but rare (people, especially western people, are missing (and found dead) in south America quite often...). And don't forget that people lives in this wild place (local tribes). They may have nothing to do with their death but touched their stuff days after while walking in the area...

- About the Panama's authorities hiding stuff : then again, nothing strange about it. Countries like south America's tend to make a secret about everything. They just don't share what they find. I remember a lot of stories like that. It feels like they don't always want to cooperate with western countries, even if there is nothing to hide. They could also be ashamed that : western people died while they were in holidays in the country (bad for the tourism) ; or that their attempts of finding the girl didn't succeed. They could feel responsible as the police were alerted April 2 and they didn't do much to find them at this point. 

- I feel like if they has been taken by strangers, drug cartel of others types of foul play, things would have been different. Every bit of information we got tend to show that Kris died first and Lisanne survived a few day afterwards, using the phone and taking photos. How can this could happened if there were some kind of foul play involved ? 


I think I said it all.  We shouldn't forget that these girls were totally confused, panicking, weak and dehydrated. So we shouldn't try to understand every moves they did. One thing is sure : they lived hell before they died. I can't imagine sleeping in this dark, scary and wild place, with any provisions, feeling yourself being weaker and weaker... What about this poor Lisanne who lived at least 5 days alone knowing her friend has died. Have you ever sleep in a forest by night ? It is scary even if you are in a safe place. I feel so bad for them. May they rest in peace now.

comments.text: In another video, the parents of Kris Kremers took the same trail to get an idea of the terrain the young women faced months earlier. They stated that there could have been no way for the ladies to have gotten lost because thick vegetation surrounds the trail on both sides. However, I think they did not factor in the following: 1) They retraced their daughter's steps already knowing the outcome. Hindsight is always viewed with 20/20 glasses; 2) The parents had guides with them and could have never gotten lost, whereas Kris and Lisanne were unguided and unfamiliar with the area; 3) Having hiked countless trails in many countries (including tropical ones) myself, there is always the main trail but animal trails and washes that look like trails, many single-track and narrow, are always present. It would be easy for inattentive newbies talking and snapping photos to start walking along one of these by mistake; 4) Kris's parents took a day trip and brought the necessary gear and supplies, but as we know based on the calls that were made on Kris and Lisanne's phones, that the two were out there for days with insufficient food and clothing. People have commented that they could have simply walked out. Seemed like Kris had gotten injured and Lisanne could not, or did not want, to leave her. With each passing day, the lack of food and exposure to the elements would have taken a toll on them mentally and physically. Other thoughts: Why did they take night shots of seemingly random things? Jungles come alive at night. I'd be doing the same thing if there were things moving around and making sounds in the darkness. Why did they call 112 (the equivalent of 911) in the Netherlands? My guess is because it was familiar to them. They had not been in Panama for very long after all and would have known that calling their homeland's emergency agency would have been more reliable than calling the hostel where they were staying. The Dutch responders would have immediately known to contact their parents to make them aware of the situation. Of course the rest of this tragic story raises more questions than answers and has many parts, but this is just my take about one of those parts.

comments.text:
• The jungle was very dense, you could see how dense the whole village is from google pictures. 

• What was unusual about Lisanne’s foot is that it seemed to have been clean cut off, not detached as a product of decomposition. 

• There’s no visible matted blood in the picture of Kris’s head. You can find a clear picture of it, it looks normal. The only thing remarkable about it is that Kris would’ve been dead by the time it was taken (because it was taken after multiple attempts of getting into her phone) and that her hair looked too clean after days of being in a humid jungle. 

• The picture that was deleted was deleted after April 1st when they were missing, because the photos on that camera are given a chronological order of numbers. 508 is jungle. 509 deleted. 509 is jungle. It’s also strange that authorities couldn’t get the picture back, because even after a picture is deleted on any camera (including that one) it would still be in the camera’s storage, just flagged as deleted. The only way to permanently delete a picture off a camera is by using a computer. 

• Assuming that they were poisoned and died, where’s the rest of their bodies? That fact that so little was found of their bodies is what really makes me think there was fault play. 

• You’re right. The backpack wasn’t waterproof. It was a low-quality nylon bag that would’ve definitely took damage had it been exposed to water, or even sun. 

• The bone bleaching isn’t consistent with sun bleaching, it was chemical. 

• Lets assume a big cat got them. Again, where are the rest of the bones? No big bones were found, only fragments. A big cat wouldn’t have been able to digest the bones. 

• People who have been there have noted that it isn’t hard to get lost there. Guides themselves sometimes get lost, but the majority of people are rescued shortly after they’re lost. 

I personally think they got lost, one of them was injured (Lisanne’s foot showed damage from falling from a considerable height or being crushed) and then someone found and killed them. Either the suspicious tour guide (he offered the girls to stay the night in his cabin in the jungle, they rejected him), or the indigenous people living in the jungle. A mass grave with 6 children and a pregnant woman was found where the indigenous people lived around the time Kris and Lisanne went missing, or shortly before I believe. And Kris and Lisanne did get lost or pass the trail only used by indigenous people. 

And I think a lot of people knew about it. The taxi driver that took them to the trail that morning was found dead shortly after, under “suspicious circumstances”. 

This case gets my mind going so hard because I want to know what happened so bad. I hope one day some truth will be uncovered, but that unfortunately seems unlikely.
